<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-08-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-08-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="754" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d754">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1491</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 651]</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-08-10">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 10, 1915</hi>.</date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 24.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose herewith
                                a full report of the proceedings in what are known as the
                                packing-houses cases, involving upwards of $12,000,000 worth of meat
                                    products.<note n="1" xml:id="d754fn1">Not printed.</note>
                                Judgment will not be given for some time. Unfortunately I am only
                                able to send one copy of the proceedings in question, which have
                                attracted more attention than any others thus far brought before the
                                prize court.</p>
                            <p>The Crown is asking for condemnation of the goods, not on the ground
                                that it was unlawful to send meat products to Scandinavian
                                countries, or, for that matter, to Germany, for the civilian
                                population, and has set up a very vaguely supported claim that there
                                was an enemy military or government destination. It is generally
                                agreed, however, that the Crown’s proof of an intended military
                                destination was exceedingly weak.</p>
                            <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert P. Skinner</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>